of modern sex education in the United States from the work of a group of reformers who coalesced around Calderone to create the Sexuality Information and Education Council of the United States (SIECUS) in 1964, to the development and use of the competing approaches known as “abstinence-based” and “comprehensive” sex education from the 1980s into the twenty-first century. A fascinating and timely read, The Transformation of American Sex Education provides a substantial contribution to the history of one of America’s most intense and protracted culture wars, and the first account of the woman who fought those battles.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBirth controlzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSex instructionzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWomen social reformerszUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAbout Your Sexuality.  aAbraham Stone.  aAbstinence-based Sex Education.  aAbstinence-plus Sex Education.  aAmerican Family Life Act (1981).  aAmerican Medical Association (AMA).  aAmerican Social Health Association.  aAnaheim, California.  aBilly James Hargis.  aBirth Control.  aChildhood sexuality.  aChristian Crusade, The.  aCommunism.  aComprehensive Sex Education.  aContraception.  aCulture Wars.  aCurriculum.  aDebra Haffner.  aDecision-making Skills.  aDeryck Calderwood.  aDouglas Kirby.  aEducation.  aEdward Steichen.  aElizabeth Blackwell.  aEmily Mudd.  aFamily Life Education.  aFeminism.  aFocus on the Family.  aFrank Lock.  aGender Inclusiveness.  aGender.  aGet Real.  aGordon Drake.  aGroup for the Advancement of Psychiatry (GAP).  aHIV/AIDS.  aHannah Stone.  aHarold Lief.  aHomosexuality.  aIncest.  aJen Slonaker.  aJohn Birch Society.  aLGBTQ+.  aLeslie Kantor.  aLester Kirkendall.  aMarriage Co